      { q: 'What does the supraorbital notch/foramen transmit?', a: 'The supraorbital nerve (branch of V1/ophthalmic) and supraorbital vessels. The notch may be converted to a complete foramen in some individuals. This is the exit point for the supraorbital nerve block.', year: '1st Prof 2015' },
      { q: 'What is the metopic suture and its clinical significance?', a: 'The metopic suture is the midline suture of the frontal bone representing fusion of two ossification centres. Persistent metopism is a normal variant. Premature fusion (craniosynostosis) causes trigonocephaly (triangular forehead deformity).', year: '1st Prof 2016' },
      { q: 'What are the consequences of frontal sinusitis spreading intracranially?', a: 'Infection spreads via the diploic veins (Breschet\'s canals) or through the posterior wall into the anterior cranial fossa, causing: meningitis, frontal lobe abscess, epidural empyema, or Pott\'s puffy tumour (subperiosteal abscess over frontal bone — osteomyelitis).', year: '1st Prof 2017' },
      { q: 'What ossification type and how many centres form the frontal bone?', a: 'Intramembranous ossification. Two primary centres (one per half) appear in the 8th fetal week and fuse at the metopic suture by age 2, though sometimes persisting. The orbital plates ossify from separate centres.', year: '1st Prof 2018' },
      { q: 'What structures form the anterior cranial fossa floor?', a: 'Orbital plate of the frontal bone (anterolateral), cribriform plate of the ethmoid (central), and lesser wings + anterior body of the sphenoid (posterior). The crista galli rises centrally for falx cerebri attachment.', year: '1st Prof 2019' }
